The sum of the primes between 100 and 200, inclusive, that are 1 or 2 more than a perfect square can be found using the Sieve of Eratosthenes.

The Sieve of Eratosthenes is a mathematical algorithm that uses a list of prime numbers to find all the prime numbers up to a given limit. In this case, we are using it to find all the prime numbers between 100 and 200, inclusive, that are 1 or 2 more than a perfect square.

To begin the Sieve of Eratosthenes, we start by creating a list of all the prime numbers up to 200. This list is called the sieve. We then add 2 to each number in the sieve, starting from 2 and going up to 200. This is done to ensure that all the prime numbers up to 200 are included in the sieve.

Next, we start from the number 1 and work our way down the sieve. We check each number in the sieve to see if it is a prime number or not. If a number is not a prime number, we remove it from the sieve and move on to the next number.

We continue this process until we have checked all the numbers in the sieve. This will give us a list of all the prime numbers up to 200, including the numbers that are 1 or 2 more than a perfect square.

The final step is to sum up the values in the list. This will give us the total sum of the primes between 100 and 200, inclusive, that are 1 or 2 more than a perfect square.

Here is the code that implements the Sieve of Eratosthenes:

```
public static void main(String[] args) {
    int n = 200;
    int m = 100;
    int sieve[] = new int[n];
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
        sieve[i] = i;
    }
    for (int i = m; i <= n; i++) {
        if (sieve[i] == 2 || sieve[i] == 3) {
            continue;
        }
        for (int j = i * i; j <= n; j += i) {
            if (sieve[j] == 1 || sieve[j] == 2) {
                sieve[j] = 0;
            }
        }
    }
    int sum = 0;
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
        if (sieve[i] == 1 || sieve[i] == 2) {
            sum += i;
        }
    }
    System.out.println("The sum of the primes between 100 and 200, inclusive, that are 1 or 2 more than a perfect square is: " + sum);
}
```

This code uses the Java programming language to implement the Sieve of Eratosthenes. The outer loop iterates from 2 to n, where n is the size of the sieve. The inner loop iterates from m to n, where m is the number of perfect squares less than n.

In each iteration of the inner loop, the code checks if the current number is a perfect square or not. If it is not a perfect square, the code removes it from the sieve and moves on to the next number.

The final step is to sum up the values in the sieve. This is done by iterating over all the numbers in the sieve and adding their values together. The sum is then stored in the sum variable.

The output of the code will be the total sum of the primes between 100 and 200, inclusive, that are 1 or 2 more than a perfect square.

