To solve this equation, we can apply the distributive property to each term in the equation.

First, distribute the $x$ in the first term:
\begin{align*}
xy + yz + zx &= x(yz + zy) + yz + zx \\
&= 4(yz + zy) + yz + zx \\
&= 8y + 4z.
\end{align*}

Next, distribute the $y$ in the second term:
\begin{align*}
xy + yz + zx &= x(yz + zy) + yz + zx \\
&= 4(yz + zy) + yz + zx \\
&= 8z + 4y.
\end{align*}

Finally, distribute the $z$ in the third term:
\begin{align*}
xy + yz + zx &= x(yz + zy) + yz + zx \\
&= 4(yz + zy) + yz + zx \\
&= 8y + 4z + 4xy.
\end{align*}

We can now simplify the equation by combining like terms:
\begin{align*}
xy + yz + zx &= 8y + 4z + 4xy \\
&= 8y + 8z + 4xy \\
&= 16y + 8z.
\end{align*}

Therefore, the value of $xy + yz + zx$ is 16.

